# Rebuild Protocol

**A rebuild changes HOW things work, never how they LOOK.**

The rebuilt app must be pixel-identical to the current app from the end user's perspective -- same navigation, same screens, same look and feel. The switch must be seamless. Users should never know anything changed. What changes is the code underneath: architecture, patterns, performance, maintainability.

**Everything is on the table.** Framework, packages, language, hosting, database, build tools -- all of it can change unless the user specifically says to keep something. The only constraint is the UX stays identical. If a completely different tech stack would be better, propose it.

---

## The #1 Rule: The Old App's UI Is the Source of Truth

This is the rule that has been broken before and caused a failed rebuild. Read it carefully.

**A rebuild is NOT building a new app from a spec. It is re-implementing the existing app's exact UI with new internals behind it.**

- The old codebase is the source of truth for everything the user sees: every page, every button, every dialog, every menu item, every form, every import/export action, every settings tab, every column in every table.
- You do NOT design new pages. You do NOT "improve" the layout. You do NOT reorganize the navigation or add/remove menu categories. You do NOT change which metrics a dashboard shows.
- Before building any page, you MUST open the old page's actual UI code and read it. Then you replicate it feature-for-feature with the new internals wired behind it.
- "It compiles and renders a table" is not done. If the old page had an Add button, an Import button, row actions, filters, and bulk actions, the new page has ALL of those, wired and working.

**The "engine vs car" failure:** Building all the backend logic (data model, pricing, permissions, state machines) and then shipping read-only skeleton pages is a FAILURE, even if the architecture is beautiful. The user cannot use an engine. Every backend capability must be wired to the exact UI control that existed in the old app.

**If the old app's source code is available, it must stay accessible for the entire rebuild.** Note its path in REBUILD-PLAN.md. Reference it on every single UI todo. Never build a page "from memory" or "from the inventory description" when the actual old code is sitting right there.

---

## How to Spawn Subagents (read this first)

Every time this protocol says "spawn a subagent," it means: **use the Task tool** with these parameters:

- `subagent_type`: `"generalPurpose"` (or `"explore"` for read-only audits)
- `model`: One of the model slugs listed below. **You MUST set this parameter.** If you omit it, the subagent runs on your own model, which defeats multi-model coverage.
- `run_in_background`: `true` (so you can spawn multiple in parallel)
- `prompt`: The full instructions for what the subagent should do. Include ALL context -- the subagent cannot see your conversation.

### Available model slugs (use these exact strings)

| Slug | Family | Cost | Best for |
|---|---|---|---|
| `composer-2.5-fast` | Composer | Cheapest | Speed audits, broad sweeps |
| `claude-opus-4-8-thinking-high` | Claude | Mid-high | Deep analysis, architecture |
| `gpt-5.5-extra-high` | GPT | High | Alternative perspective |

Use any other slugs available at runtime too (Gemini, etc.). The point is **different families, not expensive models**. Cheaper is fine for auditing.

### The rule

**Every subagent call MUST include the `model` parameter.** No exceptions. If you catch yourself spawning a subagent without explicitly setting `model`, stop and add it.

---

## Phase 0: Multi-Model Audit + History Mining

**DO NOT skip this phase. DO NOT do this yourself. You MUST spawn subagents.**

### Step 1: Orient

Read the codebase yourself. Identify the major areas (e.g. frontend, backend, database, config/infra, tests).

### Step 2: Spawn audit subagents

For EACH area you identified, spawn at least 2 subagents on DIFFERENT model families. Do this by making multiple Task tool calls in a single message with `run_in_background: true`.

**Rotation example** (3 areas, 3 families):

| Area | Subagent 1 | Subagent 2 |
|---|---|---|
| Frontend | `composer-2.5-fast` | `claude-opus-4-8-thinking-high` |
| Backend | `gpt-5.5-extra-high` | `composer-2.5-fast` |
| Database | `claude-opus-4-8-thinking-high` | `gpt-5.5-extra-high` |

NEVER use the same model slug twice for the same area. Same model = same blind spots = pointless.

Each subagent prompt must say:
> "You are auditing the [AREA] of this codebase at [PATH]. Document every feature, behavior, pattern, UX detail, route, component, API endpoint, data model, and config you find. Be exhaustive. Write your findings as a structured report. Do not skip anything -- if in doubt, include it."

### Step 3: Mine chat histories

Spawn a separate subagent to read past agent transcripts (in the `.cursor/projects/` transcripts folder) for this project. The prompt must say:
> "Read through the agent chat transcripts for this project. Find: (1) bugs fixed during the original build, (2) features added after the initial plan, (3) pain points and regressions, (4) workarounds or hacks applied under pressure, (5) anything the user corrected the agent on. Write a structured report."

### Step 4: Wait and collect

Wait for ALL audit subagents to complete. Collect their reports. Produce **BUILD-HISTORY.md** from the chat history mining results.

**DO NOT proceed to Phase 1 until every subagent has returned its report.**

---

## Phase 1: Feature Inventory + Cross-Reference

1. Collect all audit reports from all models across all areas.
2. Cross-reference reports against each other -- if Model A found something Model B missed, it goes in the inventory.
3. Cross-reference against **BUILD-HISTORY.md** -- make sure late additions, bug fixes, and post-launch features are all captured.
4. Reconcile any disagreements between models.
5. Produce **FEATURE-INVENTORY.md** -- the complete truth of what the app does today.

### The inventory is organized PAGE BY PAGE, not as a loose feature list

For every single page/screen in the app, the inventory must list:

- The route/path and the file in the old codebase that implements it.
- Every UI control on that page: buttons, links, dialogs, forms, tables (and their columns), filters, tabs, menus, import/export actions, bulk actions, row actions.
- Every navigation path into and out of the page.
- What each control does (the behavior to preserve).

This page-by-page structure is what later becomes the per-page build todos. A flat list of features is NOT good enough -- it's how features get lost.

### Capture visual snapshots of the old app

If the old app is runnable, run it and capture a screenshot of every page and every important state (empty, populated, dialogs open). Save them in a `rebuild-reference/` folder. These screenshots are the parity target for Phase 4 and Phase 5 -- you compare the rebuilt pages against them.

If the old app can't be run, the old UI source code is the parity target instead.

**DO NOT proceed to Phase 2 until FEATURE-INVENTORY.md is written, organized page-by-page, with each item tied to its old-code file.**

---

## Phase 2: Architecture Proposals

Spawn exactly 2 subagents using the Task tool, each on a DIFFERENT premier model:

- Subagent 1: `model: "claude-opus-4-8-thinking-high"`
- Subagent 2: `model: "gpt-5.5-extra-high"`

Set `run_in_background: true` for both. Spawn both in the same message so they run in parallel.

Each subagent prompt must include the full text of FEATURE-INVENTORY.md and BUILD-HISTORY.md, and say:
> "Propose a clean architecture for this app from scratch. Framework, language, hosting, and all technical choices are open. The ONLY constraint is that the end-user experience (screens, navigation, look and feel) must be pixel-identical to the current app. Old code is reference for WHAT the app does, not HOW to implement it. If the old way is already the best way for something, say so. Justify every tech stack choice in plain English."

Wait for both subagents to return before proceeding.

**DO NOT proceed to Phase 3 until both proposals are in hand.**

---

## Phase 3: Debate, Converge, and Plan in Detail

1. Spawn a premier subagent (`claude-opus-4-8-thinking-high` or `gpt-5.5-extra-high`) and give it BOTH architecture proposals. Its prompt:
   > "Review both architecture proposals below. Debate the trade-offs in plain English. Produce a unified REBUILD-PLAN.md that takes the best ideas from both. The plan must explicitly confirm: 'End-user experience is unchanged.' The plan must reference BUILD-HISTORY.md and include prevention steps for every known bug, workaround, and pain point."

2. Plan must explicitly confirm: "End-user experience is unchanged."
3. Plan must reference BUILD-HISTORY.md: known bugs, workarounds, and pain points must have explicit prevention steps.

### Granular Todos (critical)

The plan MUST be broken into the most granular, detail-oriented todos possible. General todos like "build the auth system" or "Phase 6: Admin UI" are a FAILURE. A coarse phase like "Admin UI" covering 20 pages is exactly how a rebuild ends up with 75% of the features missing.

**One page = one todo (minimum). Big pages get split further.** Each page-level todo must carry a sub-checklist of every UI control from the FEATURE-INVENTORY.md entry for that page. For example:

```
Todo 42: Rebuild /admin/orders page (old code: src/pages/admin/orders.tsx)
  [ ] Paginated orders table with columns: date, customer, total, status, payment
  [ ] Search box (searches name + order number)
  [ ] Filter presets (unpaid, needs-packing, today)
  [ ] Quick "mark paid" row action
  [ ] Bulk select + bulk actions
  [ ] Export CSV button
  [ ] Import CSV button
  [ ] Page-size selector
```

Rules for the todo list:

- Every page/screen from the inventory gets its own numbered todo with a full UI sub-checklist.
- Every API endpoint, every database table, every cron job gets its own todo.
- Every known bug from BUILD-HISTORY.md gets a todo to verify it doesn't recur.
- Each todo names the old-code file it must match.
- If a todo takes more than ~30 minutes, break it down further.
- Number every todo so nothing gets skipped.

**Sequencing rule -- UI and internals are built together, not in separate phases.** Do NOT plan "build all the backend, then build all the UI." That ordering is what caused the engine-with-no-car failure. Instead, build feature by feature: for each feature, build its internals AND its full UI in the same todo group, then verify parity before moving on.

**DO NOT proceed to Phase 4 until REBUILD-PLAN.md is written with per-page numbered todos, each with a UI sub-checklist tied to the inventory and the old-code file path.**

---

## Phase 4: Build

### Phase 4.0: Foundation + Smoke Deploy

The FIRST batch of todos should be the bare minimum scaffold: project init, config files, database connection, auth setup, a single route that renders. Then:

1. Run `tsc --noEmit` and `next build` (or equivalent). Fix all errors.
2. **Deploy to the target platform** (Vercel, Azure, etc.).
3. Verify the smoke deploy works: site loads, health endpoint returns 200, auth flow completes.
4. If the smoke deploy fails, fix it NOW. Do not build more features on a broken foundation.

This catches missing middleware, missing env vars, wrong build commands, database connection issues, and platform config gaps -- all of which have caused stacked failures in past projects when left until the end.

### Phase 4.1+: Feature Build

Execute the plan todos one by one. For EVERY page/UI todo, follow this loop -- no shortcuts:

1. **Open the old page's code first.** Read the actual UI file from the old codebase that this todo names. List every control it has.
2. **Build the new page to match it control-for-control**, with the new internals wired behind each control. Match the layout, the navigation, the menu items, the table columns, the dialogs.
3. **No stubs.** A button that doesn't do anything, a table with no actions, a "coming soon" placeholder -- these are failures, not progress. If a control existed in the old app, it works in the new one.
4. **Verify parity before marking the todo done:**
   - Run the page in the rebuilt app.
   - Compare it side-by-side against the old app's screenshot (from `rebuild-reference/`) or the old page running.
   - Walk the page's UI sub-checklist from the plan. Every item must be present and functional.
   - Only check the todo off when every sub-item passes.
5. Follow `review-protocol.mdc` before each commit -- and for rebuilds the review is a **feature-parity review**, not just a compile check (see review-protocol). Commits can trigger deploys per `deploy-awareness.mdc`.
6. Only commit and push after review passes -- never push unreviewed code.
7. Log ambiguous choices in DECISION-LOG.md per `autonomous-mode.mdc`.
8. No phase advances until its parity review passes.
9. Before advancing, read through every todo in the current phase and confirm each is marked complete WITH its UI sub-checklist fully checked (per completion checklist rule in `workflow.mdc`). "It compiles" is never the bar -- "it matches the old app and every control works" is the bar.

---

## Phase 5: Final Scope Review

This review checks whether the rebuilt app actually MATCHES the old app -- page by page, control by control. It is not a code-quality review.

### Step 1: Running-app, page-by-page parity check

Go through FEATURE-INVENTORY.md page by page. For each page:

- Open the rebuilt page in the running app.
- Compare it side-by-side against the old app's screenshot (`rebuild-reference/`) or the old app running.
- Walk every control in the inventory entry. Mark each PRESENT / PARTIAL / STUB / MISSING.
- A page only passes when every control is PRESENT and functional.

Verifying from code review alone is NOT allowed. The whole point of this phase is to catch the "it compiles but the page is a read-only stub" failure. Run it. Click it. Compare it.

### Step 2: Multi-model audit

Spawn 2 subagents on different premier models (same as Phase 2: `claude-opus-4-8-thinking-high` and `gpt-5.5-extra-high`). Each gets the finished codebase, the original FEATURE-INVENTORY.md, and the reference screenshots.

Each subagent prompt:
> "Compare this finished app against the FEATURE-INVENTORY.md below, page by page. For EVERY page, for EVERY control listed (buttons, dialogs, forms, table columns, filters, import/export, row actions, bulk actions, menu items), mark it PRESENT, PARTIAL, STUB, or MISSING with evidence from the code. Also check: (1) was anything added that wasn't in scope? (2) is the navigation/menu structure identical to the old app? (3) do all documented behaviors still work? Do not just check that it compiles -- check that each feature is actually wired and functional."

### Step 3: Report and fix

Collect both reports plus your running-app check. Produce **REBUILD-COMPLETION-REPORT.md** with a pass/fail line for every page and every control. **Any PARTIAL, STUB, or MISSING item must be fixed before declaring the rebuild done.** The rebuild is not done until the report is all-green against the inventory.
